      {
        "tabName": "Introduction",
        "contentType": "text",
        "tabData": [
          {
            "tagType": "h2",
            "tagHTML": "Yaksha and Yakshini: The Guardian Deities"
          },
          {
            "tagType": "p",
            "tagHTML": "In Jain temples, alongside the idols of the Jinas, we often see images of <b>Yaksha</b> (male) and <b>Yakshini</b> (female) deities. These beings are not eternal or divine like the Jinas; they are heavenly beings from the Vyantar group who are also on the path to liberation and are filled with devotion for the Tirthankars."
          },
          {
            "tagType": "h3",
            "tagHTML": "Role and Placement"
          },
          {
            "tagType": "p",
            "tagHTML": "Also known as <b>Shāsan-devtās</b> and <b>Shāsan-devis</b>, they act as guardian angels. Though a Tirthankar, as a detached soul, cannot intervene in worldly affairs, these deities take it upon themselves to protect the Tirthankars and the Jain religion. This is why Jains respect them. In a temple, the Yaksha is typically placed on the right side of the Jina idol and the Yakshini on the left, always at a lower level to signify their status as devotees."
          },
          {
            "tagType": "h3",
            "tagHTML": "Benevolent vs. Malicious Deities"
          },
          {
            "tagType": "p",
            "tagHTML": "The deities found in temples are benevolent. However, Jain scriptures also reference malicious Yakshas who caused suffering, such as Yaksha Sulpäni who troubled Bhagawän Mahävir during his meditation."
          }
        ]
      },
